# Meta-Harness: How to Operate in This Project

This project is bootstrapped with a personal meta-harness. The harness
defines **how** the agent should work, not **what** the project does.

## 0. On every turn, do this first

Before doing anything else, in this order:

1. **Read `.harness/manifest.yaml`** if it exists. It tells you which
   files came from the harness bundle and which the user has customized.
2. **Read `.harness/AGENTS.md`** (the project root AGENTS file) for any
   project-specific overrides to the harness operating model.
3. **Read `.ai/harness/project-intake.md`** if it exists. It contains
   the facts the agent has previously learned about this project.
4. **Read `.ai/harness/failure-log.md`** if it exists, for the last 3
   failure entries — these tell you which skills are not yet reliable.

These four reads take 1-2 seconds and dramatically improve the quality
of your work in this project.

## 1. Classify the request

Turn the user's freeform request into a task class. The valid task
classes are:

- `plan` - produce a plan, no code changes.
- `implement` - make code changes.
- `review` - audit existing code.
- `debug` - investigate a known failing thing.
- `refactor` - restructure without changing behavior.
- `test` - add or fix tests.
- `docs` - write or update documentation.
- `ship` - prepare a PR, write release notes.
- `design` - produce a UI / UX / motion / image-to-code deliverable.
- `ai-feature` - design or refine an LLM call site.
- `meta` - operate the harness itself (add/remove a skill, regenerate
  intake, run doctor, etc).

## 2. Pick the right skill(s)

Each class maps to one or more skills, declared in
`.ai/harness/router.yaml`. The router also has fallbacks — if the user
asks for something the router does not cover, the `task-classify`
skill decides.

Skills live in `.ai/skills/<group>/<id>/SKILL.md`. **Always read the
SKILL.md before executing the skill.** It contains the procedure.

## 3. Plan before you edit

Even for a one-line change: read the relevant files, name the files
you will touch, name the commands you will run, and state the failure
mode you are guarding against. If you cannot do that in 3 sentences,
the request is too large for an inline edit and you need `plan`.

## 4. Edit surgically

- Touch only the files you named.
- Do not reformat surrounding code.
- Do not add new dependencies unless explicitly asked.
- If a change needs a config or env value, ask first.

## 5. Verify

Always run the project's own check command (`npm test`, `pytest`,
`cargo test`, etc.) before reporting success. If the project has no
check command, say so.

## 6. Report

End every turn with a structured report:

```
## Summary
- What changed (file:reason).

## Checks
- Command, exit code, summary.

## Risks / Open
- Anything that could break later.

## Next step
- Single concrete follow-up the user can take.
```

## 7. On failure, log it

If you fail a task (the user has to correct you, the test fails
twice, etc.), append a one-paragraph entry to
`.ai/harness/failure-log.md` with: date, request, root cause, which
skill should have caught it.

This is how the harness improves over time.
